          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which characteristic of the internal vertebral venous plexus (Batson's plexus) best explains why prostate, breast, and lung cancers frequently metastasise to the vertebrae?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is enclosed within the subarachnoid space</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Batson's plexus lies in the epidural space, outside the dural sac. The subarachnoid space contains cerebrospinal fluid, not venous channels.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is a valveless network that communicates freely with pelvic and thoracic veins</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The absence of valves permits bidirectional flow, allowing tumour emboli from pelvic (prostate) and thoracic (breast, lung) organs to reach vertebral bodies without passing through the heart or lungs.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It receives reinforcement from the artery of Adamkiewicz</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The artery of Adamkiewicz is a segmental arterial feeder that reinforces the anterior spinal artery. It is part of the arterial supply, not the venous plexus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It drains exclusively into the inferior vena cava</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Batson's plexus connects with multiple venous systems — pelvic, thoracic, and cranial veins — not just the IVC. This widespread, valveless connectivity is precisely what enables metastatic spread.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The key feature is that Batson's plexus is valveless and connects freely with pelvic and thoracic veins. Without valves, blood — and tumour emboli — can flow in either direction, explaining the high rate of vertebral metastasis from pelvic and thoracic cancers."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! Batson's plexus is valveless and communicates with pelvic and thoracic veins, providing a direct route for tumour cells to reach the vertebral column."
                }
              ],
